node.text: Starting the day off with fried cinnamon rolls, sky-high pancakes or a three-egg scramble is hard to beat, but somehow enjoying those dishes in a place steeped in history and authenticity is even more satisfying. Such is breakfast at 𝐂𝐫𝐨𝐜𝐤𝐞𝐭𝐭’𝐬 𝐁𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐤𝐟𝐚𝐬𝐭 𝐂𝐚𝐦𝐩, a place with a rich backstory and the descendants around to tell it. Gatlinburg.com/75th

node.title: Pancakes with a side of Gatlinburg Heritage.

node.text:
After 50 years of carving, sanding, and finishing, it wouldn’t be unreasonable to think that wood might have lost its luster for Chris Compton. But it’s far from the truth.

Compton is the owner of 𝕋𝕙𝕖 𝕎𝕠𝕠𝕕 𝕎𝕙𝕚𝕥𝕥𝕝𝕖𝕣𝕤, home of handcrafted wooden masterpieces and holder of Gatlinburg’s oldest business license. The shop was founded by Compton’s father in 1944 and opened in its current location in 1968. And despite all that history, Compton continues to be fascinated by his primary material. Gatlinburg.com/75th

node.title: Carving a Place in Gatlinburg History

node.text: Decades ago, Andrew Jefferson Ely's solution to the humdrum of city life was to build a personal haven called Ely's Mill in the heart of the Smokies. Today it's his granddaughter's legacy and a rare historic connection to a bygone Gatlinburg era. Gatlinburg.com/75th

node.text:
Since our incorporation in 1945, we’ve been hard at work turning a little-known outpost of the Smokies into 𝗔𝗺𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗮'𝘀 𝗠𝗼𝘂𝗻𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻 𝗛𝗼𝗺𝗲. 
This year, we're sharing the stories behind the town and inviting everyone to join us in celebrating everything Gatlinburg. Look out for more to come…👀
